05276nam a22007335i 9780812292367DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152007pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)929158627  a97808122923677 a10.9783/97808122923672doi  a(DE-B1597)463549  a(OCoLC)928987507  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPQ6393.G3.Z64 2007eb 7aLIT0042802bisacsh04a861.31 aHelgerson, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Sonnet from Carthage :bGarcilaso de la Vega and the New Poetry of Sixteenth-Century Europe /cRichard Helgerson. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (144 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface. Diagnosis for an Essay -- tPart I. A Sonnet from Carthage -- tSonnet to Boscán from Goleta -- t1. What They Expected (. . . and What They Got) -- t2. Las armas y el furor de Marte / Arms and the fury of Mars -- t3. El arte italïano / Italian art -- t4. Aquí / Here -- t5. Me deshago / I am undone -- t6. Boscán / Boscán -- tEpilogue: Poetry of the New -- tPart II. Garcilaso's Tunisian Poems: A Bilingual Anthology -- tGarcilaso's Tunisian Poems: A Bilingual Anthology -- tEpístola a Boscán / Epistle to Boscán -- tSoneto a Mario / Sonnet to Mario -- tElegía a Boscán / Elegy to Boscán -- tElegía al duque d'Alva / Elegy to the Duke of Alba -- tOde ad Genesium Sepulvedam / Ode to Ginés de Sepúlveda -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1492 the Spanish humanist Antonio de Nebrija proclaimed that "language has always been the companion of empire." Taking as his touchstone a wonderfully suggestive sonnet that Garcilaso de la Vega wrote in 1535 from the neighborhood of ruined Carthage in North Africa, Richard Helgerson examines how the companionship of language and empire played itself out more generally in the "new poetry" of sixteenth-century Europe. Along with his friend Juan Boscán, Garcilaso was one of the great pioneers of that poetry, radically reforming Spanish verse in imitation of modern Italian and ancient Roman models. As the century progressed, similar projects were undertaken in France by Ronsard and du Bellay, in Portugal by Camões, and in England by Sidney and Spenser. And wherever the new poetry emerged, it was prompted by a sense that imperial ambition—the quest to be in the present what Rome had been in the past—required a vernacular poetry comparable to the poetry of Rome.But, as Helgerson shows, the new poetry had other commitments than to empire. Though imperial ambition looms large in Garcilaso's sonnet and others, by the end of the poem Garcilaso identifies not with Rome but with the Carthaginian queen Dido, one of empire's legendary victims. And with this startling shift, which has its counterpart in poems from all over Europe, comes one of the most important departures the poem makes from its apparent imperial agenda.Addressing these rival concerns as they arise in a single sonnet, Richard Helgerson provides a masterful and multifaceted image of one of the most vital episodes in European literary history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEuropean poetryyRenaissance, 1450-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish poetryyClassical period, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.1 aGahan, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelgerson, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniv